  "prompt": "Which one is better: the American Dream or the American dream? Dream with a capital letter or not?",
  "response": "The choice between **\"American Dream\"** (capitalized) and **\"American dream\"** (lowercase) depends on context and intended meaning:\n\n1. **Capitalized (\"American Dream\")**:  \n   Use this when referring to **the specific cultural, historical, or ideological concept** of the United States\u2014the ideal that anyone can achieve prosperity and success through hard work, regardless of background. This is treated as a proper noun.  \n   - Example: *\"The American Dream has been a central theme in U.S. literature and politics.\"*  \n\n2. **Lowercase (\"American dream\")**:  \n   Use this for **generic or individualized aspirations** that resemble the traditional ideal but are not explicitly tied to the formal concept. It becomes a common noun.  \n   - Example: *\"She pursued her own American dream of opening a small business.\"*  \n\n**Style Guides**:  \nMost authorities (AP Style, Chicago Manual of Style) recommend capitalizing \"American Dream\" when referencing the national ethos. Lowercase is appropriate for metaphorical or personal uses.  \n\n**Which is \"better\"?**  \nIf you\u2019re discussing the classic ideal, **capitalize it**. If you\u2019re describing a personal or abstract aspiration, **lowercase works**. Clarity and consistency matter most!",
